- Yeah.

11:07.814 --> 11:09.181
Bring it back, bring it back.

11:09.216 --> 11:11.150
You think at any point
you guys will move, like,

11:11.184 --> 11:13.652
more than ten inches
away from each other?

11:13.687 --> 11:15.721
You're the one I'm worried about.

11:15.755 --> 11:17.423
- What about me?
- You got the bad knee.

11:17.457 --> 11:18.691
I just run right around you.

11:18.725 --> 11:21.093
Ready.

11:21.128 --> 11:23.462
This is bulk, this is
hard to get around.

11:23.497 --> 11:24.730
One more time, one more time.

11:24.764 --> 11:26.431
Mike, take that ball,
try to get it around him.

11:26.466 --> 11:27.966
All right, fine.

11:28.000 --> 11:29.200
Look at this, man.

11:29.235 --> 11:30.235
Look at this!

11:30.270 --> 11:31.337
You guys are nothing.

11:31.371 --> 11:33.205
What the [bleep] are you guys doing?

11:33.239 --> 11:34.707
Ming's "teaching."

11:34.741 --> 11:35.808
We got customers in there.

11:35.843 --> 11:37.076
Mike's never played before.

11:37.111 --> 11:38.478
I wanted to show him some pointers.

11:38.512 --> 11:39.746
Is he just showing off or is he

11:39.781 --> 11:40.981
- actually showing him something?
- Showing off.

11:41.016 --> 11:42.149
I'm not showing off.

11:42.184 --> 11:43.250
I'm worried about him.

11:43.285 --> 11:44.485
I'm a little worried about you, too.

11:44.519 --> 11:46.020
Don't worry about me,
worry about yourself.

11:46.054 --> 11:47.188
I'm ready.

11:47.223 --> 11:49.524
All right, bring your game
tomorrow then.

11:49.559 --> 11:50.692
Let's go inside now

11:50.727 --> 11:52.594
- 'cause we're done.
- All right.

11:52.629 --> 11:55.364
I'm winded, man.

11:55.398 --> 11:57.399
We're gonna get crushed.

11:59.336 --> 12:00.736
- Is that you?
- Yeah.

12:00.771 --> 12:03.006
I self-publish autobiographical
comic books.

12:03.040 --> 12:04.007
Very impressive.

12:04.041 --> 12:05.475
I'm more interested in what's

12:05.510 --> 12:07.844
- next to this.
- Oh, my God.

12:07.879 --> 12:09.112
I brought you my prized possession.

12:09.147 --> 12:11.214
This is my lightsaber hilt.

12:11.249 --> 12:12.415
Do you think it's the real deal?

12:14.604 --> 12:16.056
Do superheroes retire?

12:16.090 --> 12:17.391
Yeah, I would have to think that,

12:17.425 --> 12:19.326
you know, superheroes retire.

12:19.360 --> 12:21.961
And you know, that's when
they look back and reflect

12:21.996 --> 12:23.296
and be like,
"Man, I saved the world."

12:23.330 --> 12:24.564
But what if, like, they retire

12:24.598 --> 12:26.432
and then they got nothing to do,
they get bored.

12:26.466 --> 12:29.267
They work at a--a box store as,
like, a greeter.

12:29.302 --> 12:31.503
He's, like, checking your
receipt as you leave.

12:31.537 --> 12:34.039
Like, that's the level
of his crime fighting.

12:34.073 --> 12:36.441
To make sure that you didn't
shoplift socks or something.

12:36.475 --> 12:39.310
It sounds to me like you're,
uh, contemplating retirement.

12:39.344 --> 12:42.146
I feel like I've already
retired--semi-retired.

12:42.180 --> 12:43.647
What have you retired from?

12:43.682 --> 12:44.815
I don't know.

12:44.850 --> 12:48.486
Hope?
[Both laugh]

12:48.521 --> 12:53.826
Oh, awesome.

12:53.860 --> 12:54.994
- Hey, how you doing?
- I'm Jonathan.

12:55.028 --> 12:56.563
- Michael.
- Hey, Michael, how's it going?

12:56.597 --> 12:57.564
You brought some stuff in?

12:57.598 --> 12:58.865
I did, I brought some, uh,

12:58.900 --> 13:00.567
original artwork for you
to take a look at.

13:00.602 --> 13:02.570
You guys might be interested in

13:02.604 --> 13:04.806
this couple of Byrne
<i>Fantastic Four</i> pages.

13:04.840 --> 13:06.040
- Is that you?
- Yeah.

13:06.074 --> 13:09.243
I self-publish autobiographical
comic books.

13:09.277 --> 13:10.978
And actually, I just got accepted into

13:11.012 --> 13:13.847
the San Diego comic con to
exhibit for the first time.

13:13.881 --> 13:15.549
- Oh, wow, congratulations.
- Yeah, yeah.

13:15.583 --> 13:16.550
What's the name of your book?

13:16.584 --> 13:18.118
It's called <i>So Buttons.</i>

13:18.152 --> 13:20.287
My grandmother used to be
like--you'd say, "So?"

13:20.321 --> 13:21.855
And she'd be like, "Sew buttons
on your underwear."

13:21.889 --> 13:23.490
That's, I guess where it--
[All laugh]

13:23.524 --> 13:24.691
That's--that was the--yeah.

13:24.725 --> 13:25.959
Kids don't say so anymore
right back now.

13:25.993 --> 13:27.660
They're more like,
"[Bleep] off, grandma."

13:27.694 --> 13:30.263
Yeah, exactly.

13:30.297 --> 13:31.964
So you just tell
the story of your life?

13:31.999 --> 13:32.965
Yeah.

13:32.999 --> 13:34.633
This is my newest one.

13:34.668 --> 13:37.337
I used to work for, uh, Robert
Redford at Sundance channel

13:37.371 --> 13:39.105
and, uh, you know, there's
a story about him in there.

13:39.139 --> 13:40.173
Very impressive.

13:40.207 --> 13:41.240
Are we gonna be in the next issue?

13:41.274 --> 13:42.408
You just might be, just might be.

13:42.442 --> 13:44.009
I met three dicks
in a comic book store.

13:44.043 --> 13:45.043
But, uh--
[All laugh]

13:45.078 --> 13:47.812
I know this is gonna sound strange,

13:47.847 --> 13:50.849
but I'm more interested in
what's next to this.

13:50.883 --> 13:52.884
The--the <i>Giant-Size Man-Thing.</i>

13:59.425 --> 14:02.327
- Can I take it out?
- Sure, take a look.

14:02.361 --> 14:04.329
This is a book that
I had as a kid, Bry.

14:04.363 --> 14:05.764
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah.

14:05.798 --> 14:07.999
He's so nice, he's picking
a log up off a deer.

14:08.033 --> 14:09.768
Oh, yeah, man-thing's
not a bad guy.

14:09.802 --> 14:11.236
He's just misunderstood.

14:11.270 --> 14:13.171
Kinda like, just wants
to be left alone.

14:13.206 --> 14:16.375
I'm starting to identify
with man-thing.

14:16.409 --> 14:18.410
Muck-encrusted
mockery of a man.

14:18.445 --> 14:19.411
Yes.

14:19.446 --> 14:20.846
If there was one thing I know

14:20.880 --> 14:26.051
about Flannigan, he loves a
<i>giant-size man thing.</i>

14:26.086 --> 14:28.353
I mean, what was marvel
thinking, publishing that?

14:28.387 --> 14:30.088
I mean, they had to know
the tongue-in-cheek, right?

14:30.122 --> 14:32.924
When they're, like, putting that
cover together and they're like,

14:32.958 --> 14:34.492
all right, let's put the title
<i>Giant-Size Man-Thing.</i>

14:34.526 --> 14:36.594
No one in that office
is not snickering?

14:36.628 --> 14:38.796
I'm sure they were like,
[Stifles laugh]

14:38.830 --> 14:39.997
"Go, Stan, go!"

14:40.031 --> 14:41.565
How much for
the <i>Giant-Size Man-Thing?</i>

14:41.599 --> 14:42.766
<i>Giant-Size Man-Thing?</i>

14:42.800 --> 14:45.802
- Yeah.
- Closer to 500.

14:45.837 --> 14:48.205
You know, I love it
but it's--even 500,

14:48.239 --> 14:50.440
it's a little bit more than
what we could spend today

14:50.475 --> 14:52.576
but, you know what,
I really dig your books.

14:52.610 --> 14:54.411
- Thanks.
- The paper, the colors.

14:54.445 --> 14:56.512
I mean, very professionally done

14:56.547 --> 14:58.548
and it's just, like,
it really would stand out,

14:58.582 --> 15:00.949
um, amongst other independent books.

15:00.984 --> 15:03.919
Would you think, uh,
would you give a thought to

15:03.954 --> 15:06.455
maybe having let us--blah,
blah, blah, blah.

15:06.489 --> 15:08.991
You had an easier time
proposing to your wife, Jesus.

15:09.025 --> 15:12.293
Do you think maybe you'd
do me the honor of letting

15:12.328 --> 15:14.195
one of your comics
go on my--I mean,

15:14.230 --> 15:15.730
I know I'm not worth it, but...

15:15.764 --> 15:19.133
I would love for you to sell
<i>So Buttons</i> in Secret Stash.

15:19.167 --> 15:21.101
He made it easy for you.

15:21.136 --> 15:23.136
I mean, yeah, I-I would
like to, um sell it.

15:23.171 --> 15:25.105
That's, uh, that's amazing
I would love that.

15:25.139 --> 15:26.240
All right, sounds like a good deal?

15:26.274 --> 15:27.675
Sounds like a good deal.

15:27.709 --> 15:29.344
Think maybe that might help
on maybe bringing

15:29.378 --> 15:31.713
the price on that
<i>Giant-Size Man-Thing</i> down?

15:31.747 --> 15:33.181
What do you think for
the <i>Giant-Size Man-Thing?</i>

15:33.215 --> 15:35.283
Let's, uh, let's take a look.

15:35.317 --> 15:36.985
150?

15:37.020 --> 15:42.024
Well, 150's a little
farther away from 500,

15:42.059 --> 15:46.429
- but what if I said...250?
- Ooh.

15:46.463 --> 15:50.333
What if I said I made
this my Black Friday special?

15:50.367 --> 15:52.135
[Laughs]

15:52.169 --> 15:54.738
<i>So buttons</i> on special.

15:54.772 --> 15:57.474
200?

15:57.509 --> 15:59.009
Um...

15:59.043 --> 16:01.712
150 is the--really,
the best I can do.

16:01.746 --> 16:03.747
175?

16:06.752 --> 16:07.986
- All right, man, deal.
- Thank you.

16:08.020 --> 16:10.856
- All right.
- [Laughs]

16:10.890 --> 16:13.058
-...75, here you go.
- Perfect.

16:13.093 --> 16:14.527
- Well, thank you.
- Thank you very much.

16:14.561 --> 16:15.828
- Thanks for bringing it in.
- Appreciate it.

16:15.863 --> 16:16.829
And, uh, here's a card.

16:16.864 --> 16:18.131
Give us a call from time to time

16:18.165 --> 16:19.633
- and we should restock--
- Check in on <i>So Buttons.</i>

16:19.667 --> 16:22.002
On <i>So Buttons</i> and I think your
thing is gonna do well here.

16:22.036 --> 16:23.270
- It's a great looking book.
- Thanks a lot.

16:23.304 --> 16:24.404
See you guys.

16:24.438 --> 16:26.306
About 175 for that's not bad, right?

16:26.341 --> 16:28.108
That'll look really nice up there.

16:28.143 --> 16:29.777
Mike, by the way, you're off next week

16:29.811 --> 16:31.646
with no pay since he bought that.

16:31.680 --> 16:33.681
You earned it.

16:36.219 --> 16:38.186
When was the last time you played?

16:38.221 --> 16:39.621
A year and a half ago.

16:39.656 --> 16:41.457
I--I'd--I'm--I think
I'll make it about

16:41.491 --> 16:43.458
10 minutes before I pull
up the mask and do a...

16:43.493 --> 16:45.260
[Imitates retching]
Projectile vomit...

16:45.294 --> 16:47.195
And then get back into the game.

16:47.230 --> 16:49.497
Big, how long are you gonna
make it before you vomit?

16:49.532 --> 16:53.000
I've already thrown up twice
so far on the way here.

16:53.035 --> 16:56.236
McCutchen, Clownface is in goal.

16:56.271 --> 16:57.838
Like, they wouldn't let
that play in the NHL.

16:57.872 --> 17:00.473
- Puffy hair coming out the sides.
- Yeah.

17:00.508 --> 17:02.274
It's one thing to paint a
mask, it's another thing

17:02.309 --> 17:03.742
to put on accoutrements and whatnot.

17:03.777 --> 17:06.645
He's accessorizing.
[All laugh]

17:06.679 --> 17:09.381
Last time I faced McCutchen, he
took a penalty shot against me

17:09.415 --> 17:12.017
as a goalie; Rushed
at me wearing pads.

17:12.050 --> 17:13.419
Yes, the penalty shot.

17:13.453 --> 17:15.587
- A goalie-on-goalie penalty shot.
- Goalie-on-goalie penalty shot.

17:15.622 --> 17:17.955
Was he shooting with
a stick or goalie stick?

17:17.991 --> 17:20.626
He had a real stick but he had
the big leg pads on, so--

17:20.660 --> 17:23.228
He was running at me with
these pads with his big leggings

17:23.262 --> 17:25.830
and so, I'm like, I have
to--if I don't block this,

17:25.866 --> 17:27.599
I look like the worst
goalie in the world

17:27.634 --> 17:29.501
because the goalie
is scoring on the goalie.

17:29.536 --> 17:31.103
And thankfully,
I caught a piece of it.

17:31.137 --> 17:32.605
You shut him down, it was impressive.

17:32.639 --> 17:34.173
But you can't trust him

17:34.207 --> 17:35.708
'cause he could just
kind of pop out the goal

17:35.742 --> 17:36.709
and try to score on you.

17:36.743 --> 17:37.977
Which I would never do.

17:38.011 --> 17:39.578
I would never run
all the way down there.

17:39.613 --> 17:41.314
Not even if the place was on fire.

17:41.348 --> 17:42.548
You want me to hack him?

17:42.582 --> 17:43.716
Yeah, would you?

17:43.750 --> 17:45.385
- Just go out and take him out.
- Slash him.

17:45.419 --> 17:48.421
Yeah.
All right, let's do this.

17:50.057 --> 17:51.057
All right, let's get this going.

17:51.091 --> 17:53.125
Five-on-five, everybody in.

17:53.160 --> 17:54.693
Everybody in.

17:54.728 --> 17:57.229
Lady Ming, what are we gonna
do, sir; what's your plan?

17:57.263 --> 18:00.666
Our plan is to run our asses
off and to not get injured.

18:00.700 --> 18:02.167
Just giving everyone
a reminder, my nickname

18:02.202 --> 18:03.936
has been "The Sieve" for many years.

18:03.970 --> 18:05.671
Don't let any past you.

18:05.705 --> 18:06.772
You ready?
Everybody in.

18:06.807 --> 18:08.975
One, two, three.
All: Puck you!

18:09.010 --> 18:10.677
All right.

18:10.711 --> 18:12.713
Let's do this.

18:24.693 --> 18:27.094
All right, let's play hockey!

18:27.129 --> 18:29.497
[Grunts]

18:29.531 --> 18:30.497
Aw, Mike!

18:30.532 --> 18:32.166
Never to Mike!

18:32.200 --> 18:34.034
Come on, Mike!

18:34.068 --> 18:35.035
Mike, Mike, Mike!

18:35.069 --> 18:36.536
I'm open!

18:36.571 --> 18:37.704
Come on!

18:37.738 --> 18:39.139
[Groans]

18:39.173 --> 18:41.975
Come on, Flannigan!

18:42.009 --> 18:45.779
Ow.

18:45.813 --> 18:48.481
Ming!

18:48.516 --> 18:50.317
Come on, Ming, find twine!

18:50.351 --> 18:52.019
[Laughs]

18:52.053 --> 18:53.620
You got checked by a girl!

18:53.654 --> 18:55.022
Shoot, shoot, shoot!

18:55.056 --> 18:57.024
- No, nope.
- Never!

18:57.059 --> 18:59.160
Oh, man.

18:59.194 --> 19:01.196
When you were younger,
it was all about the glory

19:01.230 --> 19:04.198
of blocking something and if--if
it did take a shot in the ass

19:04.233 --> 19:06.334
and it hurt, you just
manned up and stuff.

19:06.368 --> 19:08.036
But, like, I'd see someone
come and wind up.

19:08.070 --> 19:10.772
Suddenly, I'm thinking about my
tender parts and I'm like,

19:10.806 --> 19:11.839
"This is gonna hurt
for a while."

19:11.874 --> 19:13.174
[All laugh]

19:13.209 --> 19:14.308
I didn't feel young,
I'll tell you that much.

19:14.343 --> 19:15.910
Oh...

19:15.944 --> 19:17.979
Holy [bleep], man.

19:18.013 --> 19:19.714
- What do you got here?
- The entire run of

19:19.748 --> 19:20.849
<i>Crisis on Infinite Earths.</i>

19:20.883 --> 19:22.350
- Whoa.
- You know what this one is.

19:22.384 --> 19:23.885
Death of Supergirl.

19:23.919 --> 19:24.985
You're like, "Whoo,
I'm sure they're not gonna"

19:25.020 --> 19:26.253
kill anybody else that major.

19:26.288 --> 19:27.288
But you'd be wrong.

19:33.913 --> 19:35.111
- Hey.
- Hey, how's it going, man?

19:35.231 --> 19:36.169
- Good, how are you?
- I'm all right.

19:36.305 --> 19:37.194
What do you got here?

19:37.314 --> 19:38.476
Uh, well, what we got is

19:38.596 --> 19:41.611
the entire run of <i>Crisis on</i>
<i>Infinite Earths</i>

19:41.645 --> 19:43.646
with doubles of, uh,
of the later half.

19:50.553 --> 19:51.953
Did you ever hear of this, Ming?

19:51.988 --> 19:52.954
<i>Crisis on Infinite Earths?</i>

19:52.988 --> 19:54.389
Uh, I mean, vaguely.

19:54.423 --> 19:57.459
For those that, uh, don't
know, in a nutshell,

19:57.493 --> 19:59.461
give them the
<i>Crisis on Infinite Earths.</i>

19:59.495 --> 20:01.129
It was a 12-issue series
that were--

20:01.163 --> 20:05.467
DC was going to, uh,
fold all of their worlds.

20:05.501 --> 20:09.805
DC was, uh, a company built on,
like, 12 different worlds.

20:09.839 --> 20:11.473
They called it the Multiverse.

20:11.507 --> 20:14.677
So there was, like,
an earth-a, an earth-b,

20:14.711 --> 20:16.779
an earth-2, and an earth-4.

20:16.813 --> 20:17.847
An earth-x.

20:17.881 --> 20:19.115
And on all these different earths,

20:19.149 --> 20:21.116
they could take their characters

20:21.150 --> 20:24.252
and tell stories that they
wouldn't wanna normally tell.

20:24.287 --> 20:27.221
It was a fabulous series and
the first big, major event

20:27.256 --> 20:29.256
- was in issue seven.
- Right there.

20:29.291 --> 20:30.891
- Death of Supergirl.
- Right.

20:30.925 --> 20:33.393
You get the gut-punch
with issue seven.

20:33.427 --> 20:35.228
And you're like, "All right,
whoo, let me catch my breath"

20:35.263 --> 20:37.363
till next month and I'm sure
they're not gonna kill anybody

20:37.398 --> 20:40.032
"Off that major, at least until
another couple issues."

20:40.067 --> 20:42.101
But you'd be wrong.

20:42.135 --> 20:46.272
Stop assuming because right off
the bat, next month, they

20:46.306 --> 20:48.441
- kill off the flash, Barry Allen.
- Wow.

20:48.475 --> 20:50.577
And--and he stays dead
for, like, 23 years.

20:50.611 --> 20:51.711
That's huge.

20:51.746 --> 20:54.782
To save the world,
he sacrificed his life.

20:54.816 --> 20:56.684
And to sell issues.

20:56.718 --> 20:57.685
[Laughs] Yes.

20:57.719 --> 21:00.521
To sell issues.

21:00.556 --> 21:01.956
Why you wanna sell it?

21:01.990 --> 21:03.724
Uh, I'm just trying to
make a little extra money

21:03.759 --> 21:04.725
toward a film camera.

21:04.760 --> 21:06.594
I'm trying to be a film director

21:06.628 --> 21:08.129
- and editor, um...
- Oh, neat, wow.

21:08.163 --> 21:10.865
So I'm selling off the past to
pay for the future, really.

21:10.899 --> 21:13.967
Well, that--that
sounds familiar.

21:14.002 --> 21:19.272
A comic book collector sells his
collection to fund his movie.

21:19.307 --> 21:20.273
Yeah--

21:20.307 --> 21:21.274
You ever heard that story before?

21:21.308 --> 21:22.642
I am a fat guy from Jersey, so...

21:22.676 --> 21:24.910
So, the dude's trying to make a movie?

21:24.945 --> 21:25.978
Said he was inspired by you.

21:26.012 --> 21:28.047
How awesome is that, man?

21:28.081 --> 21:30.983
Do you think that's,
um, harder or easier

21:31.017 --> 21:32.118
today to do what you did?

21:32.152 --> 21:33.719
Sell your collection to make a movie?

21:33.753 --> 21:35.554
I think it's--I don't
think it's easy

21:35.588 --> 21:36.922
to sell a collection anymore.

21:36.956 --> 21:38.423
But I think it's easy to make a movie.

21:38.458 --> 21:40.659
The technology is democratized.

21:40.694 --> 21:42.562
They can make cameras that
anybody can use--

21:42.596 --> 21:44.264
- Can even make a movie on this.
- Bingo.

21:44.298 --> 21:46.566
And you can edit a movie
on that and you can upload

21:46.601 --> 21:48.401
that movie to the Internet
right on the phone.

21:48.436 --> 21:51.104
Like, to make <i>Clerks,</i>
we needed to rent equipment,

21:51.139 --> 21:53.974
lights, we needed to rent a
Steenbeck to edit it.

21:54.008 --> 21:55.943
You can do all the stuff we did
right there on a phone.

21:55.977 --> 21:57.511
So it's in the hands of everybody.

21:57.545 --> 22:00.815
It's closer--in closer reach
than it's ever been before.

22:00.849 --> 22:02.549
Problem is, with so
many people doing it,

22:02.584 --> 22:04.017
it's tough to stand out.

22:04.052 --> 22:06.553
'Cause now the field is even
wider full of competition

22:06.587 --> 22:08.054
because it's open to everybody.

22:08.089 --> 22:09.522
All right, what else you got?

22:09.556 --> 22:12.558
Uh, that is a print I got
signed by Jim Lee.

22:17.998 --> 22:21.433
I got it in 2003 at
wizard world in Philly.

22:21.468 --> 22:22.868
I looked over and I was like,
"Oh, there's Jim Lee, signing."

22:22.902 --> 22:23.869
So I was like, "Let me hop on it"

22:23.904 --> 22:25.438
before the line gets
ridiculous."

22:25.472 --> 22:26.506
Yeah, that's beautiful.

22:26.540 --> 22:28.941
Jim Lee, probably today's

22:28.976 --> 22:30.677
premier Batman artist.

22:30.711 --> 22:32.513
As far as the print goes, I mean,

22:32.547 --> 22:33.814
I'm a gigantic Jim Lee fan,
I mean--

22:33.848 --> 22:35.049
He's one of the greatest--

22:35.083 --> 22:37.618
Most popular comic artist
working today.

22:37.653 --> 22:39.287
I mean, it is just a print
with his signature

22:39.321 --> 22:41.123
so it's, like,
it's not original artwork,

22:41.157 --> 22:43.926
so, um, what are you looking
for for the print?

22:43.960 --> 22:47.829
Um, I think 20 would be
a good number on that.

22:47.864 --> 22:52.434
Um...will you take 15 for it?

22:52.469 --> 22:55.738
- ...yeah, I'll take 15 for it.
- All right.

22:55.772 --> 22:57.339
What are we looking at for the <i>Crisis?</i>

22:57.373 --> 23:01.377
For the <i>Crisis</i> I'd like to get
as close to 100 as I could.

23:03.679 --> 23:05.180
Okay.

23:05.214 --> 23:10.517
I've gotta be honest, I've seen
sets go in high grade for 25.99.

23:10.552 --> 23:11.885
- In high grade, 'cause I've--
- High grade, yeah.

23:11.920 --> 23:13.553
I've seen full sets for that amount,

23:13.588 --> 23:15.188
but usually their grade is
usually around, like,

23:15.223 --> 23:16.957
a six or seven out of a ten.

23:16.991 --> 23:20.727
Like, if I sell it here, I
might be able to get 50 for it.

23:20.761 --> 23:26.933
So, um, I'm gonna
have to offer you, um...

23:26.967 --> 23:28.534
15 bucks for a set.

23:28.569 --> 23:30.669
- 15 bucks for the set?
- Yeah.

23:30.704 --> 23:33.772
If you want the 30 for--for
these two items, then, you know,

23:33.807 --> 23:36.808
we can make that happen.

23:40.512 --> 23:42.914
I think, uh, I think 30 will do.

23:42.948 --> 23:44.349
I--I'll let these go at 30.

23:44.383 --> 23:45.750
- Okay, fantastic.
- Good.

23:45.785 --> 23:47.219
That's a little bit of karma--

23:47.253 --> 23:48.587
good karma right there, man.

23:48.621 --> 23:50.355
That's you reaching back through time.

23:50.390 --> 23:53.626
If we can script it into a comic
book to an earth-2 Kev

23:53.661 --> 23:54.828
and being like, here's the money.

23:54.862 --> 23:56.797
Go chase your dream.

23:56.831 --> 24:00.034
- All that in 30 bucks?
- My mom liked that joke.

24:00.068 --> 24:02.169
He--he probably needed a
couple more books to sell

24:02.204 --> 24:03.437
before he could
start filming, but--

24:03.471 --> 24:04.471
Right, but it's a good thing.

24:04.505 --> 24:05.472
You put him on his path.

24:05.506 --> 24:07.140
We started him off.

24:07.174 --> 24:08.675
- All right, man, thanks.
- All right, thanks a lot, guys.

24:08.709 --> 24:11.544
- All right.
- Good luck.

24:11.578 --> 24:13.112
Yo, how you feeling?

24:13.146 --> 24:14.947
I have elevated heart rate.

24:14.981 --> 24:16.281
But not in that good way.

24:16.315 --> 24:17.582
- How are you feeling--
- I feel great.

24:17.616 --> 24:18.583
You look like you're dead already.

24:18.617 --> 24:19.717
You look like you blew your [Bleep]

24:19.752 --> 24:20.852
At warm-up for some reason.

24:20.886 --> 24:22.120
Running around like
a sprite out there.

24:22.154 --> 24:23.555
- I'm all right.
- You're like a teenage boy.

24:23.589 --> 24:25.891
You shot so early we got nothing left.

24:25.925 --> 24:29.328
We have 45 minutes left to kill
on the hour we paid for.

24:29.362 --> 24:32.565
At this point, you're like,
yeah, let's play a full game!

24:32.600 --> 24:34.735
And then you're like,
15-minute game.

24:34.769 --> 24:36.537
And then you're like,
ten-minute periods?

24:36.571 --> 24:39.806
Oh, I'm done.
[All laugh]

24:39.841 --> 24:42.843
- Go.
- All right, let's do a faceoff.

24:42.878 --> 24:44.678
This guy can't shoot.

24:44.712 --> 24:46.279
Aw!

24:46.314 --> 24:48.481
Come on!

24:48.515 --> 24:51.317
What the [Bleep]?!

24:51.351 --> 24:55.721
Oh [bleep].

24:55.756 --> 24:57.789
Save the day, Walt.

24:57.824 --> 24:59.124
Time out, time out.

24:59.159 --> 25:01.360
No time out, get the [Bleep] up there.

25:01.394 --> 25:03.395
Check him, Ming.

25:06.333 --> 25:09.768
- [Laughs]
- Oh, for Christ's sake.

25:09.803 --> 25:11.804
Is that it?

25:13.674 --> 25:15.108
[Groans]

25:15.142 --> 25:17.077
[Groans]

25:17.111 --> 25:18.812
Of course, uh, the spirit is always

25:18.846 --> 25:20.981
more willing than the flesh.

25:21.016 --> 25:23.685
Flesh was very weak, insanely weak.

25:23.719 --> 25:26.654
Almost nauseatingly, vomitously weak.

25:26.688 --> 25:28.189
I don't remember...

25:28.223 --> 25:31.225
Needing to sleep quite so much
when we used to play.

25:31.259 --> 25:34.161
Literally, the first step
I took made my knee buckle

25:34.196 --> 25:35.696
and I was done after that.
[Laughs]

25:35.730 --> 25:37.031
Let me see that--how
big is it?

25:37.065 --> 25:39.066
Aw, it's like a grapefruit.

25:39.100 --> 25:41.101
I got crutches at my office
if you need them.

25:41.135 --> 25:43.636
- Bengay, icyhot.
- Rascal?

25:43.670 --> 25:46.005
I'll steal one from the
grocery store for you.

25:46.039 --> 25:48.307
For a long, long time,
we didn't play hockey.

25:48.342 --> 25:49.776
And age just crept in.

25:49.810 --> 25:53.312
Yeah, I--I'm a little thicker,
a little slower.

25:53.347 --> 25:55.515
I tell you, man, I felt tired as balls

25:55.550 --> 25:58.552
and we didn't win the game by
any stretch of the imagination.

25:58.586 --> 26:01.688
But when we got to do it again
together, it was awesome.

26:01.723 --> 26:03.824
Like, suddenly,
we weren't 40 years old.

26:03.858 --> 26:06.159
It feels like we're resuming
a conversation

26:06.194 --> 26:08.729
we left off 20 years ago.

26:08.763 --> 26:10.764
You know, but always continued

26:10.798 --> 26:12.299
every time we kind of come together.

26:12.333 --> 26:14.468
So, brings you back
to where it all started.

26:14.502 --> 26:16.203
I'm ready to go another round.

26:16.238 --> 26:17.271
[Bleep] A.

26:17.306 --> 26:18.740
I never want to get up.

26:18.774 --> 26:20.842
Who's gonna open the store?

26:20.877 --> 26:22.844
Wassup!

26:22.879 --> 26:25.013
Oh, look who it is.

26:25.047 --> 26:26.280
I brought you my prized possession.

26:26.315 --> 26:29.316
- This is my lightsaber hilt.
- No way!

26:33.609 --> 26:36.444
I mean, I was a big Batgirl
fan because you like Batman

26:36.479 --> 26:39.214
and suddenly, this is everything
you love about Batman,

26:39.249 --> 26:41.283
but you can have sex with it too.

26:41.318 --> 26:44.154
[All laugh]

26:44.188 --> 26:45.588
And so suddenly, you're like,
"I love Batgirl, she's great."

26:45.623 --> 26:47.257
- Then--
- In the show?

26:47.292 --> 26:49.693
Like Barbara Gordon in the show,
or in the comics?

26:49.727 --> 26:50.962
In the comics and in the show.

26:50.996 --> 26:52.196
I liked her in the show,
but I liked her

26:52.231 --> 26:54.465
as Batgirl in the show,
not as Barbara Gordon.

26:54.500 --> 26:55.934
Whenever she got out of the
outfit and she looked like

26:55.968 --> 26:57.168
a librarian with the short hair,

26:57.202 --> 26:58.303
I was like,
"That ain't Batgirl."

26:58.337 --> 27:00.138
But when she gets shot in

27:00.172 --> 27:02.106
<i>The Killing Joke,</i>
the Alan Moore story,

27:02.140 --> 27:04.542
the joker shoots her and
shatters her spine,

27:04.576 --> 27:07.044
and so she's been in a
wheelchair ever since, right?

27:07.078 --> 27:09.312
And that made her, I think,
ever more appealing,

27:09.347 --> 27:10.613
'cause then you just wanted
to take care of her

27:10.648 --> 27:11.781
- 'cause she's in a wheelchair.
- Really?

27:11.815 --> 27:12.983
Oh, you wouldn't leave her?

27:13.017 --> 27:14.685
No--what?!

27:14.719 --> 27:17.321
Yeah, I'm like, "You're no good to me."

27:17.355 --> 27:18.522
"You've been shot.

27:18.556 --> 27:19.823
Below the waist,
you're dead."

27:19.858 --> 27:22.726
Any girl I'm with feels
nothing below the waist.

27:34.438 --> 27:35.174
Comics.

27:35.294 --> 27:37.540
How's the stocking of
the shirts coming, Ming?

27:37.574 --> 27:40.543
Uh, could be doing better;
We've got a lot left here.

27:40.577 --> 27:42.144
Wassup!

27:42.179 --> 27:44.614
Oh, look who it is.

27:44.648 --> 27:46.082
- How you doing, Jay?
- How you guys doing?

27:46.116 --> 27:47.283
What are you doing in town?

27:47.317 --> 27:48.518
You know what I'm doing in town, man.

27:48.552 --> 27:49.585
Kevin asked me to come in

27:49.620 --> 27:50.887
and check things out, so--

27:50.921 --> 27:51.887
- What does that mean?
- I wanted to come in and--

27:51.922 --> 27:52.888
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

27:52.923 --> 27:54.023
What are you talking about?

27:54.057 --> 28:00.897
He wants to see how things are
going, bro.

28:00.931 --> 28:02.365
Uh, did I hear this right?

28:02.399 --> 28:06.503
Mewes came to visit and, like,
worked at the Stash for a day?

28:06.537 --> 28:10.874
He told me you told him to
come down and work at the Stash.

28:10.908 --> 28:12.809
That--doesn't that sound
a little sit-com to you?

28:12.843 --> 28:14.377
I'm like, "Your punishment
is you gotta"

28:14.412 --> 28:16.380
go work at
the Stash, young man."

28:16.414 --> 28:17.547
And he's like, "Aw!"

28:17.582 --> 28:19.350
See him fly across the country
in graphic--

28:19.384 --> 28:21.085
[all laugh]

28:21.119 --> 28:24.255
What new books
are--are here today?

28:24.289 --> 28:26.257
Ming, he is not getting
those books for free.

28:26.291 --> 28:28.725
I don't care what you've gotta
do or what you have to say.

28:28.760 --> 28:31.194
You cannot let him walk out
of here with those books.

28:31.229 --> 28:32.763
All right, full price.

28:32.797 --> 28:35.366
Give him a discount,
you heartless bastard.

28:35.400 --> 28:36.834
I know, his name's on the store.

28:36.868 --> 28:39.469
I'm gonna take these
and then I'm gonna come back

28:39.503 --> 28:40.870
when the new books get here.

28:40.905 --> 28:42.372
All right, I'm gonna
let Ming handle this.

28:42.406 --> 28:43.439
And I need to get a shirt.

28:43.474 --> 28:45.074
I spilled something on my shirt.

28:45.108 --> 28:47.677
It's a little chilly out so I'm
probably gonna take a hoodie.

28:47.711 --> 28:50.446
That's cool, Ming'll take care of you.

28:50.481 --> 28:52.215
You know this was my idea to
make hoodies, right?

28:52.250 --> 28:53.617
He invented the hoodie.

28:53.651 --> 28:55.919
You know, one day,
I was like, my head is cold.

28:55.953 --> 28:58.088
I wish there was a shirt
with a hood on it.

28:58.122 --> 29:00.690
No, no, I didn't invent
the hoodies but...

29:00.725 --> 29:01.958
- All right, is this it?
- Wait, why are you--

29:01.993 --> 29:03.160
why are you ringing this up, bro?

29:03.194 --> 29:04.695
What do you mean,
why am I ringing it in?

29:04.729 --> 29:06.530
'Cause that--wait,
I'm not gonna pay for these.

29:06.564 --> 29:07.865
Well put them back if you're
not gonna pay for them.

29:07.899 --> 29:09.099
- What do you mean?
- You've gotta pay for them.

29:09.134 --> 29:10.367
- Wait a sec.
- I'll give you a discount.

29:10.402 --> 29:11.969
- Turn around and look at him.
- Okay.

29:12.003 --> 29:13.603
What's on his chest.

29:13.638 --> 29:15.005
- Oh, the--your face?
- Yeah.

29:15.039 --> 29:16.974
Yeah, but it's not--you really
think that, like, um--

29:17.008 --> 29:19.475
Like, Orville Redenbacher
walks into a food store

29:19.510 --> 29:21.310
and he's like,
I'm gonna take this popcorn.

29:21.345 --> 29:22.745
All right, you're right.

29:22.780 --> 29:25.481
You're right, none of that
makes sense.

29:25.516 --> 29:26.482
But, yo, I'm broke.

29:26.517 --> 29:28.151
[All laugh]

29:28.185 --> 29:31.654
Yo, let me get a dollar.

29:31.689 --> 29:34.190
Jay, of course, you know from
the movies; Jay and silent Bob.

29:34.225 --> 29:36.359
But, uh, for those that don't
know, uh, Jason Mewes,

29:36.394 --> 29:39.797
the guy that plays Jay, um, you
know is the dude who kind of

29:39.831 --> 29:41.065
Peter Pan-ish, man.

29:41.099 --> 29:43.134
Like, forever young.

29:43.168 --> 29:45.570
The best way to describe Mewes is,

29:45.604 --> 29:50.909
this is what happens to Bart
Simpson when he grows up.

29:50.943 --> 29:52.510
Can you just pay for the books, Ming?

29:52.544 --> 29:54.212
Ming, just pay for the books then.

29:54.246 --> 29:57.448
Ring him in and use your card
and everything's cool, bro.

29:57.482 --> 29:59.649
Oh, use my card?

29:59.684 --> 30:01.217
Yeah.

30:01.252 --> 30:02.552
[Laughs]

30:02.586 --> 30:03.720
I'll pay you back, though.

30:03.754 --> 30:06.222
Like the ten bucks
you owe me from 1996?

30:06.256 --> 30:08.157
I'll pay you back, yeah, yeah.

30:08.191 --> 30:12.028
[All laugh]

30:12.062 --> 30:17.067
All right, it's $103.45,
there's tax.

30:17.101 --> 30:18.068
I'm gonna go take a lunch.

30:18.103 --> 30:19.370
When I get back, if you want,

30:19.404 --> 30:21.806
I'll run the front and you guys
can take a break.

30:21.840 --> 30:22.907
I wanna go with you.

30:22.941 --> 30:23.942
Let's go to lunch, dude?

30:23.976 --> 30:24.943
Do you think--

30:24.977 --> 30:25.944
do you think you could add, like,

30:25.978 --> 30:27.379
20 bucks, dude, then we can get

30:27.413 --> 30:30.215
cash from the Reggie just so I
can grab, like, some pizza?

30:30.249 --> 30:31.283
Yeah, we can do that, we can do that.

30:31.317 --> 30:32.517
Wha--no.

30:32.552 --> 30:33.919
I'll get you back, dude.

30:33.953 --> 30:36.955
- All right, all right.
- 20 bucks, that's it.

30:42.628 --> 30:44.229
He thinks of you, he's like,
"This pigeon.

30:44.263 --> 30:46.631
I can take money out
of him like he's an ATM."

30:46.665 --> 30:48.866
I still don't know how that
happened, though.

30:48.900 --> 30:50.434
How did I whip out
my credit card and--

30:50.469 --> 30:51.936
'Cause you got starstruck, dude.

30:51.970 --> 30:53.137
You see him still and you're like,

30:53.172 --> 30:55.573
"He's that boy from the movies!"
You know?

30:55.607 --> 30:57.608
And you're like, "Here's all my
money, Mr. Mewes."

30:57.642 --> 30:58.876
We're going to lunch, I'll be back.

30:58.910 --> 31:00.044
If you guys wanna take a break--

31:00.078 --> 31:01.979
Don't hurry back, take your time.

31:02.013 --> 31:03.914
What just happened?

31:03.949 --> 31:05.182
You got robbed.

31:05.216 --> 31:10.854
[Laughs]

31:10.889 --> 31:12.556
- Hey, man, how you doing?
- How you doing, buddy?

31:12.590 --> 31:13.557
Good to see you.

31:13.592 --> 31:15.126
What's the occasion?

31:15.160 --> 31:16.928
I got too much comics.

31:16.962 --> 31:18.163
My man cave's in serious jeopardy.

31:18.197 --> 31:20.265
My wife is giving me a lot of heat.

31:20.299 --> 31:22.333
Your manhole's in jeopardy?

31:22.368 --> 31:24.402
Man c--man cave.

31:24.437 --> 31:25.938
I think you lost him.

31:25.972 --> 31:28.507
Walt and I talk about--it's
where guys keep their comics.

31:28.541 --> 31:29.975
- Oh, okay.
- And their stuff.

31:30.010 --> 31:32.644
So, my wife said you gotta
go through this stuff

31:32.679 --> 31:34.914
and, you know, get rid of some of it.

31:34.948 --> 31:37.116
So you gotta get rid
of some to get some more.

31:37.150 --> 31:38.317
It's--it's like
the ongoing thing.

31:38.351 --> 31:40.285
- All right.
- What have you got there, man?

31:40.319 --> 31:45.223
Al Harvey, who created Richie
Rich, Casper, asked Steve Ditko,

31:45.257 --> 31:49.260
who co-created spider-man,
to create a 3d comic.

31:56.402 --> 31:57.402
Where'd you get this at?

31:57.436 --> 31:59.170
Uh, it was a long story.

31:59.204 --> 32:02.440
We don't have that long.
[Both laugh]

32:02.474 --> 32:05.309
When do I come here like
clockwork, ever week?

32:05.343 --> 32:06.643
- On Wednesdays.
- Wednesdays.

32:06.677 --> 32:07.744
When you put out the new books.

32:07.778 --> 32:09.613
Back in the day, books used to

32:09.647 --> 32:11.349
- come out on Friday, remember?
- Right.

32:11.383 --> 32:14.185
So on Fridays...

32:14.219 --> 32:16.587
...this guy who my friend used
to say was going through

32:16.622 --> 32:19.224
mid-life crisis and
had a suit on and...

32:19.258 --> 32:21.859
So he buys a collection
from an old lady.

32:21.894 --> 32:24.363
Her husband had a stationary store...

32:24.397 --> 32:26.131
...you spent $32 on
comics this week...

32:26.166 --> 32:28.033
...toy store this weekend
and I ran into Mike and

32:28.068 --> 32:29.401
I had my daughter and he had his...

32:29.436 --> 32:31.070
...I remember the day
my dad got an ulcer.

32:31.104 --> 32:34.206
I wanted to get the,
uh, Death Star droid--

32:34.240 --> 32:35.707
Dude, how much do you want for this?

32:35.742 --> 32:36.909
Yeah, are you trying to sell them?

32:36.943 --> 32:38.477
Or are you just coming
here to tell a story?

32:38.511 --> 32:40.012
You know, m--maybe.

32:40.046 --> 32:43.215
On the Internet, I've seen it
as high as 145.

32:43.250 --> 32:44.250
Yeah, but you know what?

32:44.284 --> 32:45.918
You, as well as I, know that

32:45.953 --> 32:48.287
there's very few people looking
for this stuff right now.

32:48.321 --> 32:50.990
Every day that this book is not sold,

32:51.024 --> 32:53.225
someone who was interested
in it, is dead.

32:53.259 --> 32:54.726
They die by the minute.

32:54.760 --> 32:57.095
A man of your capability
can move things.

32:57.129 --> 32:59.564
If not, put it in a more capable hand.

32:59.598 --> 33:01.599
Oh, there goes two more
of the potential customers

33:01.633 --> 33:03.734
have died by the time we're
having this conversation.

33:03.769 --> 33:05.836
I had a vague interest in them.

33:05.871 --> 33:07.305
I felt though, I could
get them at a price

33:07.339 --> 33:08.406
that I was comfortable with.

33:08.440 --> 33:10.675
But, unfortunately, Jay felt that

33:10.709 --> 33:13.945
it was not a price that was fair
to our regular customer.

33:13.980 --> 33:15.847
So what do you think, Walter?

33:15.882 --> 33:19.918
Uh, I'll give you 15 bucks
for <i>Captain 3-D...</i>

33:19.953 --> 33:23.022
And <i>True 3-D...</i>

33:23.056 --> 33:27.793
Yeah.

33:27.828 --> 33:30.663
50 bucks for all four of them.

33:30.697 --> 33:32.097
He starts haggling against us?

33:32.132 --> 33:33.866
He starts haggling against us.

33:33.900 --> 33:35.701
Against the family?

33:35.735 --> 33:37.670
Fredo.
[Kiss noise]

33:37.704 --> 33:39.504
He is the Fredo of this bunch, man.

